Question 5: Write a C program to print \n on the screen.

-------------------------
-------------------------
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    printf("\\n\n");
    return 0;
}
Question 6: Write a C program to print %d on the screen.

-------------------------
-------------------------
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    printf("%%d\n");
    return 0;
}
Question 7: Write a C program containing declaration of three variables (of type int, char and float), also assign some values to them and print values of all three variables using single printf().

-------------------------
-------------------------
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int num = 10;
    char letter = 'A';
    float floating = 3.14;

    printf("num: %d, letter: %c, floating: %f\n", num, letter, floating);
    return 0;
}
Question 8: Explore following format specifiers on the internet - %i, %g, %lf

%i: Used for printing integers.
%g: Used for printing floating-point numbers in either %f or %e format, depending on the value.
%lf: Used for printing double-precision floating-point numbers.
Question 9: Write a C program to print a character stored in a char variable, also print its ASCII code.

-------------------------
-------------------------
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    char ch = 'A';
    printf("Character: %c, ASCII code: %d\n", ch, ch);
    return 0;
}
Question 10: How to convert a Decimal number into a Binary number and vice versa.

Decimal to Binary Conversion: Divide the decimal number by 2 repeatedly and keep track of the remainders. The remainders, read in reverse order, give you the binary equivalent.
Binary to Decimal Conversion: Multiply each digit of the binary number by 2 raised to the power of its position and sum the results.
